  "signature": "ed25519:7e3a1c9f2b5d8e0a4c7f1b3d6e9a2c5f8b1d4e7a0c3f6b9d2e5a8c1f4b7d0e3a",
  "hasCredibilityFactor": [
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Software quality assurance",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "FEA software (Ansys Mechanical) operates under a validated quality management system with documented version control and regression testing.",
      "rationale": "All three FEA codes used in the ensemble (FDA in-house, Ansys 2021R2, DePuy Synthes internal) are subject to documented SQA procedures including version-controlled source repositories, regression test suites, and periodic re-verification against benchmark problems. Ansys holds ISO 9001 certification. FDA in-house code is maintained under a 21 CFR Part 11-compliant software development life cycle."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical code verification",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Code verification benchmarks demonstrate correct implementation of governing equations for implicit nonlinear structural analysis.",
      "rationale": "Each FEA code was verified against NAFEMS benchmark problems LE1 and NL1 for linear and nonlinear structural response respectively. Patch tests for contact elements were performed and passed. Results were compared across codes to confirm consistent numerical behavior prior to application to the pedicle screw geometry."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Mesh convergence study demonstrates QoI change less than 5% between medium and fine mesh densities.",
      "rationale": "A three-level mesh convergence study was conducted on the pedicle screw-rod construct model. Coarse (85k elements), medium (210k elements), and fine (520k elements) meshes were evaluated. Stiffness QoI changed by 3.1% between medium and fine; yield force changed by 2.7%. The medium mesh was selected for production runs, providing acceptable accuracy at tractable computational cost."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Iterative solver residuals converge to machine precision tolerance; Newton-Raphson convergence confirmed at each load step.",
      "rationale": "Nonlinear analyses used full Newton-Raphson iteration with force and displacement convergence criteria of 0.1% and 0.5% respectively. All load steps converged within 15 iterations. Solver residuals were monitored and confirmed to be below 1e-6 at each increment. No load step bisections were required beyond the initial plasticity onset regime."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Model setup reviewed by independent analyst; boundary conditions and loading documented against ASTM F1717 test standard.",
      "rationale": "The FEA model setup was independently reviewed by a second analyst at each participating organization. Boundary conditions replicate the ASTM F1717 test fixture geometry: inferior block fixed, superior block loaded in displacement control along the construct axis at 5 degrees offset. Loading rate and fixture compliance were matched to experimental protocol. Discrepancies identified during review were resolved prior to production runs."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Continuum elasto-plastic constitutive model with isotropic hardening accepted as appropriate for titanium alloy pedicle screw under monotonic loading.",
      "rationale": "Ti-6Al-4V pedicle screw and rod components are modeled using a von Mises yield criterion with isotropic hardening calibrated to tensile coupon data. The UHMWPE vertebral body surrogate blocks are modeled as linear elastic, consistent with the low strain levels observed in that region. Frictional contact (mu=0.3) is applied at all screw-rod and screw-block interfaces. The model form is consistent with established practice for metallic spinal implant FEA and is supported by the literature."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Material properties sourced from coupon testing of production-lot material; geometric inputs from CMM measurements of test specimens.",
      "rationale": "Elastic modulus, yield strength, and ultimate tensile strength for Ti-6Al-4V were characterized from five tensile coupons machined from the same production lot as test specimens (mean E=114.2 GPa, sigma_y=928 MPa). UHMWPE block properties were taken from manufacturer datasheet with literature corroboration. Screw and rod geometry were measured by CMM on three representative specimens; mean dimensions used for nominal model. Dimensional variability was propagated through the Monte Carlo UQ analysis. All material and geometric inputs are fully documented in the supporting technical file."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "N≥10 test specimens from production-representative manufacturing lot tested across two independent laboratories.",
      "rationale": "Eleven non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screw constructs were tested: six at Laboratory A (FDA CDRH) and five at Laboratory B (DePuy Synthes). All specimens were drawn from a single production lot and are representative of the commercial device. Specimen traceability was maintained throughout. The sample size provides sufficient statistical power to characterize experimental variability for comparison with the UQ-informed FEA ensemble."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Test conditions span the range of physiologically relevant loading scenarios including at minimum two load configurations.",
      "rationale": "Testing was conducted under a single load configuration (static compression-bending per ASTM F1717 at 5-degree offset) consistent with the regulatory submission requirement. While this configuration is the standard reference condition, only one test condition was evaluated; torsion and fatigue loading were not included in this validation activity. This factor is below the required level and is noted as a limitation of the current validation scope. The decision record acknowledges this gap and accepts the residual uncertainty given the regulatory context."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "FEA model inputs are demonstrably equivalent to experimental specimen and test fixture parameters within documented tolerances.",
      "rationale": "CMM measurements of test specimens were used directly to parameterize the FEA geometry. Fixture compliance was measured experimentally and incorporated as a spring boundary condition. Material property inputs were derived from coupons from the same lot. A formal input equivalency table was prepared mapping each experimental parameter to its FEA counterpart, with documented justification for any simplifications. All equivalency assessments are within accepted engineering tolerances."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Quantitative comparison metric E/uval < 1.96 for all QoIs; percentage difference < 10%.",
      "rationale": "Three QoIs were compared: construct stiffness, yield force, and force at 40 mm displacement. For each QoI, the validation metric E/uval was computed per ASME V&V 40 Eq. 6-1, incorporating both experimental uncertainty (uexp from inter-specimen and inter-laboratory variability) and simulation numerical uncertainty (unum from mesh convergence). Results: stiffness E/uval=1.18 (6.2% diff), yield force E/uval=1.31 (7.3% diff), force at 40mm E/uval=1.42 (8.1% diff). All three QoIs pass both acceptance criteria."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "QoIs are directly linked to the clinical failure mode of interest and to the regulatory submission performance criteria.",
      "rationale": "Construct stiffness, yield force, and force at 40 mm displacement are the three QoIs specified in ASTM F1717 and referenced in FDA guidance for spinal pedicle screw systems. These quantities directly characterize the structural performance relevant to the clinical risk of implant fracture or excessive deformation under in vivo loading. The QoIs are therefore directly relevant to the COU decision."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Validation activities use the same device design, material, and loading mode as the COU; any differences are documented and justified.",
      "rationale": "The validation activity uses production-representative non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screws under the same ASTM F1717 compression-bending protocol as the regulatory COU. The FEA model geometry, material assignments, and boundary conditions are directly derived from the test specimens and fixture. The validation is therefore highly relevant to the COU. The sole noted difference is that the validation is conducted at a single load level; extrapolation to other load levels relies on the validated constitutive model."
    }
  ],
  "hasWeakener": [],
  "hasDecisionRecord": {
    "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/decision/nagaraja-cou1-dr-001",
    "type": "DecisionRecord",
    "actor": "https://uofa.net/synth/actor/nagaraja-credibility-team",
    "role": "Credibility assessment team",
    "outcome": "Accepted",
    "rationale": "All 13 V&V 40 credibility factors were assessed. Twelve of thirteen factors meet or exceed the required credibility level. The Test Conditions factor achieves Gradation 2 against a required Gradation 3 due to the single load configuration tested; this gap is accepted given that ASTM F1717 compression-bending is the regulatory standard reference condition and the model risk level (3) is offset by medium model influence and medium decision consequence. Uncertainty quantification was conducted via comprehensive Monte Carlo sampling across all model inputs, and all three QoIs satisfy the pre-established acceptance criteria (E/uval < 1.96; percentage difference < 10%). The overall credibility package is sufficient to support the regulatory submission decision.",
    "decidedAt": "2026-04-19T00:00:00Z"
  },
